Q1. Visualizing patient trajectory

Visualizing a patientâs encounters in a health care system is a common task in clinical data analysis. In this question, we will visualize a patientâs ADT (admission-discharge-transfer) history and ICU vitals in the MIMIC-IV data.

Q1.1 ADT history

A patientâs ADT history records the time of admission, discharge, and transfer in the hospital. This figure shows the ADT history of the patient with subject_id 10001217 in the MIMIC-IV data. The x-axis is the calendar time, and the y-axis is the type of event (ADT, lab, procedure). The color of the line segment represents the care unit. The size of the line segment represents whether the care unit is an ICU/CCU. The crosses represent lab events, and the shape of the dots represents the type of procedure. The title of the figure shows the patientâs demographic information and the subtitle shows top 3 diagnoses.

Q2.2 Summary and visualization

How many unique subject_id? Can a subject_id have multiple ICU stays? Summarize the number of ICU stays per subject_id by graphs.

How many unique subject_id?

There are 50920 unique subject_id.

icustays_tble |>
  distinct(subject_id) |>
  nrow()
[1] 50920

Can a subject_id have multiple ICU stays?

The numbers of unique subject_id and stay_id are different, which means a subject_id can have multiple ICU stays.

icustays_tble |>
  distinct(stay_id) |>
  nrow()
[1] 73181

Summarize the number of ICU stays per subject_id by graphs.

icustays_tble |>
  group_by(subject_id) |>
  summarize(n = n()) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = n)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Number of ICU stays per subject_id",
       x = "Number of ICU stays",
       y = "Number of subject_id")

According to the MIMIC-IV documentation,

All dates in the database have been shifted to protect patient confidentiality. Dates will be internally consistent for the same patient, but randomly distributed in the future. Dates of birth which occur in the present time are not true dates of birth. Furthermore, dates of birth which occur before the year 1900 occur if the patient is older than 89. In these cases, the patientâs age at their first admission has been fixed to 300.
